<p>
The suffix @HI{{@EM{{kaneru}}}} is used in formal spoken or written Japanese to express politely that the speaker cannot do something owing
to a specific circumstance.
This form can only be used as a suffix with verbs that take a human first person subject.

<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{kon'na@FG{{@KJ{{tall^}}:kouka}}na@FG{{@KJ{{}}:oku}}ri@FG{{@KJ{{thing}}:mono}},@FG{{@KJ{{}}:itada}}ki@EM{{kanemasu}}.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      I cannot accept such an expensive gift.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

@BGRND{{}}
<p>
@HI{{machi@EM{{kaneru}}}} is the only exception to the above rule, in that it takes a third person subject.

<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{midorisan',go@FG{{@KJ{{lord^person}}:shujin'}}gao@KJ{{wait}}chi@EM{{kane}}yo.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      Midori, your husband is waiting for you with impatience (lit: cannot wait).
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

@BGRND{{}}
<p>
When the main predicate is in the progressive form, that is @HI{{@EM{{kaneteiru}}}}, a subject in the third person is allowed.

<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KJ{{he}}ha@KJ{{private}}no@KJ{{spirit^hold}}chiwo@FG{{@KJ{{quantity}}:haka}}ri@EM{{kaneteiru}}youda.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      He appears to find it hard to understand my feelings.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

@BGRND{{}}
<p>
<a name="kanenai">When</a> suffix is in the negative, @HI{{@EM{{kanenai}}}}, the double negative means not "cannot do" but "it is very possible" or "might".
The result in question is a negative one.
This form is used as a suffix with verbs that take either a third person human subject or a third person non-human subject.

<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@FG{{@KJ{{outburst^move}}:houdou}}suru@FG{{@KJ{{rouse}}:o}}kori@EM{{kanenai}}youna@FG{{@KJ{{tense^urge}}:kinpaku}}shita
      @FG{{@KJ{{feelings^but*of*course}}:joukyou}}datta.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      It was such a tense situation that even a riot could have taken place.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

@BGRND{{}}
<p>
No potential forms can take @HI{{@EM{{kaneru}}}}, except @HI{{wakaru}} and @HI{{dekiru}}.

<table class="sentence">
